The single point that is well below the main cluster drags the least-squares line toward itself.  
Because it sits near the middle of the x-range but far below the other y-values, the algorithm must “compromise,” so the fitted line tilts downward (its slope becomes smaller) and the whole line shifts slightly lower than it would have been without that point. Consequently:

• the slope is flatter than it otherwise would be;  
• predicted scores for small study times are a bit higher, and for large study times a bit lower, than they would be without the outlier;  
• the correlation coefficient is reduced (here to 0.69).

In short, the outlier pulls the line of best fit downward and decreases both the slope and the strength of the linear relationship.
